[src:canary-deployment/continuous-deployment] Continuous deployment contrasts with *continuous delivery* (also abbreviated CD), a similar approach in which software functionalities are also frequently delivered and deemed to be potentially capable of being deployed, but are actually not deployed.
[src:canary-deployment/continuous-deployment] As such, continuous deployment can be viewed as a more complete form of automation than continuous delivery.
[src:canary-deployment/continuous-deployment] Continuous deployment has been adopted by software companies such as Meta, Microsoft, Atlassian, IBM, Adobe, and Tesla.
[src:canary-deployment/continuous-deployment] Continuous deployment extends the principles of continuous integration and delivery by including fully automated production deployment without the need for manual approval, instead relying on rigorous automated testing.
[src:canary-deployment/continuous-deployment] Reviews may still take place in the form developer-developer code reviews, but the need for intermediary reviewers such as a change-advisory board is minimized.
[src:canary-deployment/continuous-deployment] Because code changes are deployed automatically, continuous deployment requires a much higher standard of automated testing, as test quality determines the reliability of releases.
[src:canary-deployment/continuous-deployment] Without this, the risk of introducing production failures outweighs the benefits of deployment automation.
[src:canary-deployment/continuous-deployment] In addition, continuous deployment emphasizes small incremental changes and dark launches through the use of feature toggles.
[src:canary-deployment/continuous-deployment] Developers can deploy code into production months before a public release by gradually adding functionality in small chunks, verifying stability, and then enabling the feature for users when it is considered ready.
[src:canary-deployment/continuous-deployment] Continuous deployment removes the need to wait for releases, as once a change passes internal testing it is automatically deployed to production.
[src:canary-deployment/continuous-deployment] This allows for shorter time-to-market and more frequent releases, which in turn increases customer satisfaction and provides companies with more marketing opportunities.
[src:canary-deployment/continuous-deployment] A major motivation for continuous deployment is that deploying software into the field more often makes it easier to find, catch, and fix bugs.
[src:canary-deployment/continuous-deployment] Deploying small, incremental changes makes it easier to trace the origin of bugs, since issues will be isolated to a recent and relatively small code change.
[src:canary-deployment/continuous-deployment] Under this methodology, new software features can be released to customers more quickly and frequently after their development, accelerating the delivery of value to customers and enhancing customer satisfaction.
[src:canary-deployment/continuous-deployment] Teams can begin to collect customer feedback almost immediately, driving rapid innovation of relevant features.
[src:canary-deployment/continuous-deployment] Continuous delivery requires a significant investment in adequate test coverage, real-time monitoring, and strong continuous integration pipelines to prevent bugs from reaching production.
[src:canary-deployment/continuous-deployment] Customers may also find software that is constantly changing creates a learning curve which can negatively affect their experience.
[src:canary-deployment/continuous-deployment] Moving to continuous delivery is also a culture shift for developers who are accustomed to traditional release cycles, often requiring a proven DevOps process.
[src:canary-deployment/continuous-deployment] Adopting this process requires collaboration among multiple stakeholders, including development teams, leadership, operations, and quality assurance.
[src:canary-deployment/continuous-deployment] In an environment in which data-centric microservices provide the functionality, and where the microservices can have multiple instances, continuous deployment consists of instantiating the new version of a microservice and retiring the old version once it has drained all the requests in flight.
[src:canary-deployment/deployment-environment] In software deployment, an **environment** or **tier** is a computer system or set of systems in which a computer program or software component is deployed and executed.
[src:canary-deployment/deployment-environment] This structured release management process allows phased deployment (rollout), testing, and rollback in case of problems.
[src:canary-deployment/deployment-environment] Environments may vary significantly in size: the development environment is typically an individual developer's workstation, while the production environment may be a network of many geographically distributed machines in data centers, or virtual machines in cloud computing.
[src:canary-deployment/deployment-environment] Code, data, and configuration may be deployed in parallel, and need not connect to the corresponding tier—for example, pre-production code might connect to a production database.
[src:canary-deployment/deployment-environment] Deployment architectures vary significantly, but, broadly, the tiers are bookended by starting at *development* (DEV) and ending at *production* (PROD).
[src:canary-deployment/deployment-environment] A common 4-tier architecture is *development, testing, model, production* (DEV, TEST, MODL, PROD), with software being deployed to each in order.
[src:canary-deployment/deployment-environment] Other common environments include Quality Control (QC), for acceptance testing; sandbox or experimental (EXP), for experiments that are not intended to proceed to production; and Disaster Recovery, to provide an immediate fallback in case of problems with production.
[src:canary-deployment/deployment-environment] Another common architecture is development, testing, acceptance and production (DTAP).
[src:canary-deployment/deployment-environment] This language is particularly suited for server programs, where servers run in a remote data center; for code that runs on an end user's device, such as applications (apps) or clients, one can refer to the user environment (USER) or local environment (LOCAL) instead.
[src:canary-deployment/deployment-environment] Exact definitions and boundaries between environments vary – test may be considered part of dev, Acceptance may be considered part of test, part of stage, or be separate, etc.
[src:canary-deployment/deployment-environment] The main tiers are progressed through in order, with new releases being deployed (*rolled out* or *pushed*) to each in turn.
[src:canary-deployment/deployment-environment] Experimental and recovery tiers, if present, are outside this flow – experimental releases are terminal, while recovery is typically an old or duplicate version of production, deployed after production.
[src:canary-deployment/deployment-environment] In case of problems, one can *roll back* to the old release, most simply by pushing the old release as if it were a new release.
[src:canary-deployment/deployment-environment] The last step, deploying to production ("pushing to prod") is the most sensitive, as any problems result in immediate user impact.
[src:canary-deployment/deployment-environment] For this is often handled differently, at least being monitored more carefully, and in some cases having phased rollout or only requiring flipping a switch, allowing rapid rollback.
[src:canary-deployment/deployment-environment] It is best to avoid a name like Quality Assurance (QA); QA doesn’t mean software testing.
[src:canary-deployment/deployment-environment] Testing is important, but it is different from QA.
[src:canary-deployment/deployment-environment] Sometimes deployment is done outside of this regular process, primarily to provide urgent or relatively minor changes, without requiring a full release.
[src:canary-deployment/deployment-environment] This may consist of a single patch, a large service pack, or a small hotfix.
[src:canary-deployment/deployment-environment] The table below describes a finely-divided list of tiers.
[src:canary-deployment/deployment-environment] The development environment (dev) is the environment in which changes to software are developed, most simply an individual developer's workstation.
[src:canary-deployment/deployment-environment] The environment on an individual workstation, in which changes are worked on and tried out, may be referred to as the *local environment* or a sandbox.
[src:canary-deployment/deployment-environment] The purpose of the test environment is to allow human testers to exercise new and changed code via either automated checks or non-automated techniques.
[src:canary-deployment/deployment-environment] After the developer accepts the new code and configurations through unit testing in the development environment, the items are moved to one or more test environments.
[src:canary-deployment/deployment-environment] Upon test failure, the test environment can remove the faulty code from the test platforms, contact the responsible developer, and provide detailed test and result logs.
[src:canary-deployment/deployment-environment] If all tests pass, the test environment or a continuous integration framework controlling the tests can automatically promote the code to the next deployment environment.
[src:canary-deployment/deployment-environment] Different types of testing suggest different types of test environments, some or all of which may be virtualized to allow rapid, parallel testing to take place.
[src:canary-deployment/deployment-environment] For example, automated user interface tests may occur across several virtual operating systems and displays (real or virtual).
[src:canary-deployment/deployment-environment] Performance tests may require a normalized physical baseline hardware configuration, so that performance test results can be compared over time.
[src:canary-deployment/deployment-environment] Availability or durability testing may depend on failure simulators in virtual hardware and virtual networks.
[src:canary-deployment/deployment-environment] Tests may be serial (one after the other) or parallel (some or all at once) depending on the sophistication of the test environment.
[src:canary-deployment/deployment-environment] A significant goal for agile and other high-productivity software development practices is reducing the time from software design or specification to delivery in production.
[src:canary-deployment/deployment-environment] Highly automated and parallelized test environments are important contributors to rapid software development.
[src:canary-deployment/deployment-environment] A stage, staging or pre-production environment is an environment for testing that exactly resembles a production environment.
[src:canary-deployment/deployment-environment] It seeks to mirror an actual production environment as closely as possible and may connect to other production services and data, such as databases.
[src:canary-deployment/deployment-environment] For example, servers will be run on remote machines, rather than locally (as on a developer's workstation during dev, or on a single test machine during the test), which tests the effects of networking on the system.
[src:canary-deployment/deployment-environment] The primary use of a staging environment is to test all the installation/configuration/migration scripts and procedures before they're applied to a production environment.
[src:canary-deployment/deployment-environment] This ensures all major and minor upgrades to a production environment are completed reliably, without errors, and in a minimum of time.
[src:canary-deployment/deployment-environment] Another important use of staging is performance testing, particularly load testing, as this is often sensitive to the environment.
[src:canary-deployment/deployment-environment] Staging is also used by some organizations to preview new features to select customers or to validate integrations with live versions of external dependencies.
[src:canary-deployment/deployment-environment] The production environment is also known as *live*, particularly for servers, as it is the environment that users directly interact with.
[src:canary-deployment/deployment-environment] Deploying to production is the most sensitive step; it may be done by deploying new code directly (overwriting old code, so only one copy is present at a time), or by deploying a configuration change.
[src:canary-deployment/deployment-environment] These in turn may be done all at once or gradually, in phases.
[src:canary-deployment/deployment-environment] When deploying a new release to production, rather than immediately deploying to all instances or users, it may be deployed to a single instance or fraction of users first, and then either deployed to all or gradually deployed in phases, in order to catch any last-minute problems.
[src:canary-deployment/deployment-environment] This is similar to staging, except actually done in production, and is referred to as a *canary release*, by analogy with coal mining.
[src:canary-deployment/deployment-environment] This adds complexity due to multiple releases being run simultaneously, and is thus usually over quickly, to avoid compatibility problems.
[src:canary-deployment/deployment-environment] Development, Staging and Production are known and documented environment variables in ASP.NET Core.
[src:canary-deployment/deployment-environment] Depending on the defined variable, different code is executed and content rendered, and different security and debug settings are applied.
[src:canary-deployment/feature-toggle] A **feature toggle** in software development provides an alternative to maintaining multiple feature branches in source code.
[src:canary-deployment/feature-toggle] A condition within the code enables or disables a feature during runtime.
[src:canary-deployment/feature-toggle] In agile settings the toggle is used in production, to switch on the feature on demand, for some or all the users.
[src:canary-deployment/feature-toggle] Thus, feature toggles do make it easier to release often.
[src:canary-deployment/feature-toggle] Advanced roll out strategies such as canary roll out and A/B testing are easier to handle.
[src:canary-deployment/feature-toggle] Continuous delivery is supported by feature toggles, even if new releases are not deployed to production continuously.
[src:canary-deployment/feature-toggle] The feature is integrated into the main branch even before it is completed.
[src:canary-deployment/feature-toggle] The version is deployed into a test environment once, the toggle allows to turn the feature on, and test it.
[src:canary-deployment/feature-toggle] Software integration cycles get shorter, and a version ready to go to production can be provided.
[src:canary-deployment/feature-toggle] The third use of the technique is to allow developers to release a version of a product that has unfinished features.
[src:canary-deployment/feature-toggle] These unfinished features are hidden (toggled) so that they do not appear in the user interface.
[src:canary-deployment/feature-toggle] There is less effort to merge features into and out of the productive branch, and hence allows many small incremental versions of software.
[src:canary-deployment/feature-toggle] A feature toggle is also called **feature switch**, **feature flag**, **feature gate**, **feature flipper**, or **conditional feature**.
[src:canary-deployment/feature-toggle] Feature toggles are essentially variables that are used inside conditional statements.
[src:canary-deployment/feature-toggle] Therefore, the blocks inside these conditional statements can be toggled 'on or off' depending on the value of the feature toggle.
[src:canary-deployment/feature-toggle] This allows developers to control the flow of their software and bypass features that are not ready for deployment.
[src:canary-deployment/feature-toggle] A block of code behind a runtime variable is usually still present and can be conditionally executed, sometimes within the same application lifecycle; a block of code behind a preprocessor directive or commented out would not be executable.
[src:canary-deployment/feature-toggle] A feature flag approach could use any of these methods to separate code paths in different phases of development.
[src:canary-deployment/feature-toggle] The main usage of feature toggles is to avoid conflict that can arise when merging changes in software at the last moment before release, although this can lead to toggle debt.
[src:canary-deployment/feature-toggle] Toggle debt arises due to the dead code present in software after a feature has been toggled on permanently and produces overhead.
[src:canary-deployment/feature-toggle] This portion of the code has to be removed carefully as to not disturb other parts of the code.
[src:canary-deployment/feature-toggle] Feature toggles usually require lifecycle management beyond the conditional statements used to implement them.
[src:canary-deployment/feature-toggle] A study of practitioner material and developers from 38 companies identified 17 practices for feature-toggle use, grouped into management, initialization, implementation, and clean-up practices.
[src:canary-deployment/feature-toggle] Commonly reported practices included recording metadata for each toggle, defining a default value, logging changes made to toggles, and using dedicated tools to manage them.
[src:canary-deployment/feature-toggle] Research on Google Chrome found that feature toggles can support rapid releases, trunk-based development, and A/B testing, but also require additional maintenance when toggles remain in the codebase for long periods.
[src:canary-deployment/feature-toggle] Later work on feature-toggle structure similarly noted that toggles may increase code complexity, introduce dead code, and reduce maintainability if they are not removed or organized after their purpose has ended.
[src:canary-deployment/feature-toggle] There are two main types of feature toggle.
[src:canary-deployment/feature-toggle] One is a release toggle, which the developer determines to either keep or remove before a product release depending on its working.
[src:canary-deployment/feature-toggle] The other is a business toggle, which is kept because it satisfies a different usage compared to that of the older code.
[src:canary-deployment/feature-toggle] Feature groups consist of feature toggles that work together.
[src:canary-deployment/feature-toggle] This allows the developer to easily manage a set of related toggles.
[src:canary-deployment/feature-toggle] A **canary release** (or canary launch or canary deployment) allows developers to have features incrementally tested by a small set of users.
[src:canary-deployment/feature-toggle] Feature flags are an alternate way to do canary launches and allow targeting by geographic locations or even user attributes.
[src:canary-deployment/feature-toggle] If a feature's performance is not satisfactory, then it can be rolled back without any adverse effects.
[src:canary-deployment/feature-toggle] It is named after the use of canaries to warn miners of toxic gases.
[src:canary-deployment/feature-toggle] Martin Fowler states that a release toggle, a specific type of feature toggle, "should be your last choice when you're dealing with putting features into production".
[src:canary-deployment/feature-toggle] Instead, it is best to break the feature into smaller parts that each can be implemented and safely introduced into the released product without causing other problems.
[src:canary-deployment/feature-toggle] Feature-toggling is used by many large websites including Flickr, Disqus, Etsy, Reddit, Gmail and Netflix, as well as software such as Google Chrome Canary or Microsoft Office.
[src:canary-deployment/rolling-release] A rolling release model is different from a staged or "staggered" rollout, in which an update is gradually made available to an increasing percentage of users for testing or bandwidth reasons.
[src:canary-deployment/rolling-release] An example of a rolling release would be Arch Linux, where new packages and updates roll in constantly, and significant changes to the distribution may occur at any time by the developers.
[src:canary-deployment/rolling-release] This is in contrast to Ubuntu Linux, which has biannual releases, with the only major changes after a release being security updates or significant bug fixes.
[src:canary-deployment/rolling-release] Rolling release development models are one of many types of software release life cycles.
[src:canary-deployment/rolling-release] Some modern Distributed SQL databases such as YugabyteDB also support this feature.
[src:canary-deployment/rolling-release] A rolling release is typically implemented using small and frequent updates.
[src:canary-deployment/rolling-release] However, simply having updates does not automatically mean that a piece of software is using a rolling release cycle; for this, the philosophy of developers must be to work with one code branch as opposed to discrete versions.
[src:canary-deployment/rolling-release] When the rolling release is employed as the development model, software updates are typically delivered to users by a package manager on the user's personal computer, accessing through the internet a remote software repository (often via a download mirror) stored on an internet file server.
[src:canary-deployment/software-deployment] Deployment can involve activities on the producer (software developer) side or on the consumer (user) side or both.
[src:canary-deployment/software-deployment] Deployment to consumers is a hard task because the target systems are diverse and unpredictable.
[src:canary-deployment/software-deployment] Software as a service avoids these difficulties by deploying only to dedicated servers that are typically under the producer's control.
[src:canary-deployment/software-deployment] Because every software system is unique, the precise processes or procedures within each activity can hardly be defined.
[src:canary-deployment/software-deployment] Therefore, "deployment" should be interpreted as a *general process* that has to be customized according to specific requirements or characteristics.
[src:canary-deployment/software-deployment] When computers were extremely large, expensive, and bulky (mainframes and minicomputers), the software was often bundled together with the hardware by manufacturers and provided for free.
[src:canary-deployment/software-deployment] A pivotal moment occurred in 1969 when IBM, influenced by antitrust lawsuits, began charging for software and services separately from hardware.
[src:canary-deployment/software-deployment] This "unbundling" effectively created the modern software industry, turning software into a commercial product.
[src:canary-deployment/software-deployment] Early deployment processes were highly structured; the Lincoln Labs Phased Model, developed in 1956 for the SAGE air defense system, introduced sequential phases that influenced later methodologies.
[src:canary-deployment/software-deployment] This approach was formalized in the waterfall model, which became dominant after being described by Winston Royce in 1970.
[src:canary-deployment/software-deployment] It led to infrequent, costly, and lengthy release cycles, often taking years.
[src:canary-deployment/software-deployment] If business software needed to be installed, it often required an expensive, time-consuming visit by a systems architect or a consultant.
[src:canary-deployment/software-deployment] For complex, on-premises installation of enterprise software today, this is sometimes still the case.
[src:canary-deployment/software-deployment] The development of mass-market software for the new age of microcomputers in the 1980s brought new forms of software distribution – first cartridges, then Compact Cassettes, then floppy disks, and later (in the 1990s and beyond) optical media, the internet and flash drives.
[src:canary-deployment/software-deployment] This shift meant that software deployment could be left to the customer.
[src:canary-deployment/software-deployment] During this period, alternatives to the rigid waterfall model emerged.
[src:canary-deployment/software-deployment] The Spiral Model, proposed by Barry Boehm in 1988, introduced a risk-driven, iterative approach that challenged waterfall's linear structure and paved the way for more flexible, agile methodologies.
[src:canary-deployment/software-deployment] As customer-led deployment became standard, it was recognized that configuration should be user-friendly.
[src:canary-deployment/software-deployment] In the 1990s, tools like InstallShield became popular, providing installer wizards that eliminated the need for users to perform complex tasks like editing registry entries.
[src:canary-deployment/software-deployment] In pre-internet software deployments, releases were by nature expensive and infrequent affairs.
[src:canary-deployment/software-deployment] The spread of the internet fundamentally transformed software distribution and made end-to-end agile software development viable by enabling rapid collaboration and digital delivery.
[src:canary-deployment/software-deployment] The foundations for modern rapid deployment were laid in the 1990s when Kent Beck developed Continuous Integration as a core practice of Extreme Programming, advocating for developers to integrate their work daily.
[src:canary-deployment/software-deployment] The advent of cloud computing and software as a service (SaaS) in the 2000s further accelerated this trend, allowing software to be deployed to a large number of customers in minutes.
[src:canary-deployment/software-deployment] This shift also meant deployment schedules were now typically determined by the software supplier, not the customers.
[src:canary-deployment/software-deployment] Such flexibility led to the rise of continuous delivery as a viable option, especially for web applications.
[src:canary-deployment/software-deployment] Modern deployment strategies that build upon these principles include blue–green deployment and canary release deployment.
